('Costa Rica', 'POC2', 'yes', 'Article 31\r\n\"El territorio de Costa Rica será asilo para todo perseguido por razones políticas.\"\r\n\r\nBoth the Migration Act and its Refugee Regulations do not incorporate the broader refugee definition enshrined in the 1984 Cartagena Declaration, and neither the Refugee Unit nor the Administrative Migration Tribunal have been applying it when determining refugee status. \r\n\r\nThe Constitutional Court Ruling No. 11264-2007 of 8 August 2007 stated that the 1984 Cartagena Declaration was recognized and reaffirmed in the San Jose Declaration on Refugees and Displaced Persons of 7 December in 1994, and ruled that the 1984 Cartagena Declaration is a human rights instrument that is valid within the territory of Costa Rica. The Constitutional Court is one of the four rooms of the Costa Rican Supreme Court that fulfills a function of constitutional control, as it regulates the Constitutional Jurisdiction to guarantee the supremacy of constitutional norms and principles, the international law valid in Costa Rica, as well as fundamental rights and freedoms that are enshrined in the Political Constitution and in international human rights instruments valid in Costa Rica. \r\n\r\nIn its recent Judicial Review ruling 0103-2014-IV of 28 November 2014, the Administrative Court concluded that the Constitutional Court had incorporated the Cartagena Declaration into the domestic legal system as a constitutional parameter, and therefore Article 13 of the Constitutional Jurisdiction Act, mandates compliance for all judicial and administrative bodies. \r\n\r\n'),
('Costa Rica', 'POC3', 'yes', 'Article 31\r\n\"El territorio de Costa Rica será asilo para todo perseguido por razones políticas.\"'),
